<BaseLayout title="About" description="Jacob Boudreau is a Cognitive Science PhD student at Stony Brook University studying speech perception and psycholinguistics.">

  <h1>Jacob Boudreau</h1>
  <p class="text-muted" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-size: 0.95rem;">
    Ph.D. Student, Cognitive Science · Stony Brook University
  </p>

  <p>
    I'm a first-year PhD student in the Department of Psychology at Stony Brook University,
    working with <a href="#" target="_blank">Dr. Sahil Luthra</a> in the
    <a href="#" target="_blank">Speech Perception & Cognition Lab</a>.
    My research focuses on how listeners adapt to variability in speech — across talkers,
    social contexts, and learning histories.
  </p>

  <p>
    I'm particularly interested in the intersection of <strong>speech perception</strong>,
    <strong>psycholinguistics</strong>, and <strong>cognitive neuroscience</strong>:
    how the brain tracks a talker's phonetic signature, and how that knowledge shapes
    real-time word recognition. I also care a lot about methodology — especially how
    tools like social network surveys can help us study language as it actually exists in communities.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before Stony Brook, I completed an M.A. in Linguistics (with a Data Analytics emphasis)
    at the University of Iowa, where I worked with Dr. Ethan Kutlu on heritage speaker
    sentence processing and cross-linguistic phonetic cue learning. I also hold B.A. degrees
    in English & Creative Writing and Linguistics from Iowa, and I continue to write fiction.
  </p>

